In C#, the `GC.SuppressFinalize(this)` method call is used to inform the garbage collector that the finalization of the current object should be suppressed. This is often used in classes that implement the `IDisposable` interface, as part of the `Dispose` method.

When an object is marked for finalization, the garbage collector will add it to the finalization queue. However, by calling `GC.SuppressFinalize(this)`, you are essentially telling the garbage collector not to finalize the object when it eventually gets collected. This can be useful when you have already explicitly cleaned up any resources in the `Dispose` method, and there is no need for the finalizer to do any additional work.

Here is an example of using `GC.SuppressFinalize(this)` in a class that implements `IDisposable`:

```csharp
using System;

public class SampleClass : IDisposable
{
    private bool disposed = false;

    // Dispose method to release resources
    public void Dispose()
    {
        Dispose(true);
        GC.SuppressFinalize(this);
    }

    protected virtual void Dispose(bool disposing)
    {
        if (!disposed)
        {
            if (disposing)
            {
                // Clean up managed resources
            }

            // Clean up unmanaged resources

            disposed = true;
        }
    }

    // Finalizer
    ~SampleClass()
    {
        Dispose(false);
    }
}
```

In this example, the `GC.SuppressFinalize(this)` call in the `Dispose` method ensures that if the object is collected by the garbage collector, its finalizer will not be executed since we have already cleaned up the resources in the `Dispose` method.

